	<h6>SPSS Statistics</h6>
	<h2><strong>Interpreting</strong> the SPSS Statistics output from a Friedm=
an test</h2>

	<p>SPSS Statistics will generate either two or three tables, depending on =
whether you selected to have descriptives and/or quartiles generated in add=
ition to running the Friedman test.</p>
=09
	<h3>Descriptive Statistics Table</h3>
=09
	<p>The <strong>Descriptives Statistics</strong> table will be produced if =
you selected the <span class=3D"cs-variable">Quartiles</span> option:</p>

	<div class=3D"spss-image spss-image-text" style=3D"max-width:364px;max-hei=
ght:156px;">
	<img src=3D"https://statistics.laerd.com/spss-tutorials/img/ft/friedman-te=
st-7.gif" data-src=3D"img/ft/friedman-test-7.gif" alt=3D"'Descriptive Stati=
stics' table for the Friedman test in SPSS Statistics. Shows 'N' &amp; 'Per=
centiles' for each variable" width=3D"100%">
	<p>Published with written permission from SPSS Statistics, IBM Corporation=
.</p>
	</div>
=09
	<p>This is a very useful table because it can be used to present descripti=
ve statistics in your results section for each of the time points or condit=
ions (depending on your study design) for your dependent variable. This use=
fulness will be presented in the "Reporting the Output" section later.</p>

	<h3>Ranks Table</h3>

	<p>The <strong>Ranks</strong> table shows the mean rank for each of the re=
lated groups, as shown below:</p>
=09
	<div class=3D"spss-image spss-image-text" style=3D"max-width:151px;max-hei=
ght:135px;">
	<img src=3D"https://statistics.laerd.com/spss-tutorials/img/ft/friedman-te=
st-8.png" data-src=3D"img/ft/friedman-test-8.png" alt=3D"'Ranks' table for =
the Friedman test in SPSS Statistics. Shows 'Mean Rank' for each variable" =
width=3D"100%">
	<p>Published with written permission from SPSS Statistics, IBM Corporation=
.</p>
	</div>

	<p>The Friedman test compares the mean ranks between the related groups an=
d indicates how the groups differed, and it is included for this reason. Ho=
wever, you are not very likely to actually report these values in your resu=
lts section, but most likely will report the median value for each related =
group.</p>

	<h3>Test Statistics Table</h3>

	<p>The <strong>Test Statistics</strong> table informs you of the actual re=
sult of the Friedman test, and whether there was an overall statistically s=
ignificant difference between the mean ranks of your related groups. For th=
e example used in this guide, the table looks as follows:</p>

	<div class=3D"spss-image spss-image-text" style=3D"max-width:152px;max-hei=
ght:152px;">
	<img src=3D"https://statistics.laerd.com/spss-tutorials/img/ft/friedman-te=
st-9.png" data-src=3D"img/ft/friedman-test-9.png" alt=3D"'Test Statistics' =
table for the Friedman test in SPSS Statistics. Shows 'N', 'Chi-Square', 'd=
f' &amp; 'Asymp. Sig.'" width=3D"100%">
	<p>Published with written permission from SPSS Statistics, IBM Corporation=
.</p>
	</div>
=09
	<p>The table above provides the test statistic (<span style=3D"font-family=
:Cambria Math;font-size:18px;">=CF=87</span><sup>2</sup>) value ("<strong>C=
hi-square</strong>"), degrees of freedom ("<strong>df</strong>") and the si=
gnificance level ("<strong>Asymp. Sig.</strong>"), which is all we need to =
report the result of the Friedman test. From our example, we can see that t=
here is an overall statistically significant difference between the mean ra=
nks of the related groups. It is important to note that the Friedman test i=
s an omnibus test, like its parametric alternative; that is, it tells you w=
hether there are overall differences, but does not pinpoint which groups in=
 particular differ from each other. To do this you need to run post hoc tes=
ts, which will be discussed after the next section.</p>

	<h6>SPSS Statistics</h6>
	<h2><strong>Reporting</strong> the results from a Friedman test (<strong>w=
ithout</strong> post hoc tests)</h2>

	<p>You can report the Friedman test result as follows:</p>=20
=09
	<div class=3D"statement">
		<ul><li class=3D"gen active">General</li></ul>
		<p class=3D"gen-content">There was a statistically significant difference=
 in perceived effort depending on which type of music was listened to whils=
t running, =CF=87<sup>2</sup>(2) =3D 7.600, <em>p</em> =3D 0.022.</p>
	<div style=3D"clear:both;"></div>
	</div>
=09
	<p>You could also include the median values for each of the related groups=
. However, at this stage, you only know that there are differences <em>some=
where</em> between the related groups, but you do not know <em>exactly</em>=
 where those differences lie. Remember though, that if your Friedman test r=
esult was not statistically significant, you should not run post hoc tests.=
</p>

	<h3>Post Hoc Tests</h3>

	<p>To examine where the differences actually occur, you need to run separa=
te <a href=3D"https://statistics.laerd.com/spss-tutorials/wilcoxon-signed-r=
ank-test-using-spss-statistics.php">Wilcoxon signed-rank tests</a> on the d=
ifferent combinations of related groups. So, in this example, you would com=
pare the following combinations:</p>

	<ul>
	<li>None to Classical.</li>
	<li>None to Dance.</li>
	<li>Classical to Dance.</li>
	</ul>
=09
	<p>You need to use a Bonferroni adjustment on the results you get from the=
 Wilcoxon tests because you are making multiple comparisons, which makes it=
 more likely that you will declare a result significant when you should not=
 (a Type I error). Luckily, the Bonferroni adjustment is very easy to calcu=
late; simply take the significance level you were initially using (in this =
case, 0.05) and divide it by the number of tests you are running. So in thi=
s example, we have a new significance level of 0.05/3 =3D 0.017. This means=
 that if the <em>p</em> value is larger than 0.017, we do not have a statis=
tically significant result.</p>
=09
	<p>Running these tests (see how with our <a href=3D"https://statistics.lae=
rd.com/spss-tutorials/wilcoxon-signed-rank-test-using-spss-statistics.php">=
Wilcoxon signed-rank test</a> guide) on the results from this example, you =
get the following result:</p>
=09
	<div class=3D"spss-image spss-image-text" style=3D"max-width:430px;max-hei=
ght:169px;">
	<img src=3D"https://statistics.laerd.com/spss-tutorials/img/ft/friedman-te=
st-10.gif" data-src=3D"img/ft/friedman-test-10.gif" alt=3D"'Test Statistics=
' table for post hoc tests for the Friedman test in SPSS Statistics" width=
=3D"100%">
	<p>Published with written permission from SPSS Statistics, IBM Corporation=
.</p>
	</div>
=09
	<p>This table shows the output of the Wilcoxon signed-rank test on each of=
 our combinations. It is important to note that the significance values hav=
e not been adjusted in SPSS Statistics to compensate for multiple compariso=
ns =E2=80=93 you must manually compare the significance values produced by =
SPSS Statistics to the Bonferroni-adjusted significance level you have calc=
ulated. We can see that at the <em>p</em> &lt; 0.017 significance level, on=
ly perceived effort between no music and dance (dance-none, <em>p</em> =3D =
0.008) was statistically significantly different.</p>

	<h6>SPSS Statistics</h6>
	<h2><strong>Reporting</strong> the results from a Friedman test (<strong>w=
ith</strong> post hoc tests)</h2>
=09
	<p>You can report the Friedman test with post hoc tests results as follows=
:</p>=20
	<div class=3D"statement">
		<ul><li class=3D"gen active">General</li></ul>
		<p class=3D"gen-content">There was a statistically significant difference=
 in perceived effort depending on which type of music was listened to whils=
t running, <span style=3D"font-family:Cambria Math;font-size:18px;">=CF=87<=
/span><sup>2</sup>(2) =3D 7.600, <em>p</em> =3D 0.022. Post hoc analysis wi=
th Wilcoxon signed-rank tests was conducted with a Bonferroni correction ap=
plied, resulting in a significance level set at <em>p</em> &lt; 0.017. Medi=
an (IQR) perceived effort levels for the no music, classical and dance musi=
c running trial were 7.5 (7 to 8), 7.5 (6.25 to 8) and 6.5 (6 to 7), respec=
tively. There were no significant differences between the no music and clas=
sical music running trials (<em>Z</em> =3D -0.061, <em>p</em> =3D 0.952) or=
 between the classical and dance music running trials (<em>Z</em> =3D -1.81=
1, <em>p</em> =3D 0.070), despite an overall reduction in perceived effort =
in the dance vs classical running trials. However, there was a statisticall=
y significant reduction in perceived effort in the dance music vs no music =
trial (<em>Z</em> =3D -2.636, <em>p</em> =3D 0.008).</p>
	<div style=3D"clear:both;"></div>
	</div>

